awyers in-house, having the payroll managers in-house, and all of this is t=
o focus on the customer experience. We=E2=80=99re very much at the company,=
 I=E2=80=99m an engineer, so as much as a lot of the operational processes =
are gapped by people because you need to productize it, you need to underst=
and it.

And some people want to have this local HR touch, they want to have someone=
 locally that they can talk to that speaks their language and that can help=
 them. We=E2=80=99re moving billions of dollars a month across 450 differen=
t bank accounts. Think about the fact that in Kenya we have to run payroll =
with our local bank account there, that part is pretty crazy. Plus the auto=
mation of all the different processes, like onboarding, hiring, filling the=
 different forms, all the local forms, there=E2=80=99s no way you cannot. S=
ure it=E2=80=99s not deep, deep, deep tech, but there=E2=80=99s no way you =
can build a company, even to the stage where we are, we=E2=80=99ve got stro=
ng automations level and processes at scale.

*That makes total sense. I like the point about integration, because if you=
 think about your place in the value chain, you have all these different co=
mpanies, your customers interacting with Deel and then you are interacting =
with all these however many employees are on your platform, and you want to=
 have the full point-of-integration somewhere in that value chain, that def=
initely makes sense.*

*One more question: How do you acquire customers? You talked about how COVI=
D dropped a lot of large enterprises in your lap. I could see you starting =
out like a lot of backend companies =E2=80=94 they start with startups beca=
use it=E2=80=99s just easier, and then if the startup grows big, then now t=
hey have big customers, whereas going into large companies is very hard bec=
ause they=E2=80=99re already with SAP or they=E2=80=99re already with Workd=
ay or whatever it might be, but you ended up where you actually had big com=
panies coming to you out of desperation. How has your customer acquisition =
approach shifted, if it has at all? Are you more of a big company player no=
w on accident and if startups want to join up they can, how do you think ab=
out that broadly?*

*AB:* I think we=E2=80=99re very lucky in a way where most companies in our=
 ecosystem, they usually come with a solution and they=E2=80=99re like, =E2=
=80=9CWell, if you want to use us, you got to rip up everything you have an=
d then put us in place=E2=80=9D for HR, payroll, et cetera. With Deel, it=
=E2=80=99s kind of like that core bundling and unbundling experience. You c=
an come to us just to run payroll in Kenya for you or you can come to us ju=
st to employ that person in Singapore, with one specific visa.

*Which by the way I think makes sense because you are integrated organizati=
onally, you can more easily offer modular interfaces to people on the outsi=
de.*

*AB:* Exactly. This whole modular interface is something that makes us real=
ly special. You come in just to employ that person in that country and then=
 if we do a good job when you=E2=80=99re like, I can land-and-expand there,=
 =E2=80=9COh, talk to me about that product, talk to me about that product=
=E2=80=9D. That=E2=80=99s how we=E2=80=99re able to come into the accounts =
and start really growing, and at the same time we=E2=80=99re able to serve =
companies who have some large enterprise.

We=E2=80=99re learning, because the company, if you think about it, the pro=
duct is turning four years old on the 19th of March, a very young company. =
But we=E2=80=99re starting to have bigger companies that are saying, =E2=80=
=9COkay, I want the full stack=E2=80=9D, so that go-to-market is quite inte=
resting. Like you said, we started with startups, because when we started, =
I couldn=E2=80=99t exactly say that we had compliance figured out in all th=
ose countries or have entities in all those countries, and we grew with our=
 customers.

Today, we have a pretty healthy mix of companies and generally I think we=
=E2=80=99re able to have a product that=E2=80=99s self-onboarding and self-=
usable enough that most of the startups are able to get going really fast, =
you just need to educate them on what happens if you terminate that person =
in that country and how much is that truly going to cost you. Then some of =
the bigger enterprises, we truly are able to penetrate with one specific mo=
dule and be true partners to them in terms of how do they think through the=
 next stage of evolution of the company.

Most of the companies we=E2=80=99re talking to right now and the conversati=
on always evolves. CHROs, CPOs, they always go through different phases. An=
d right now, most of the big companies are talking to us thinking, =E2=80=
=9COkay, I need to cut cost. I=E2=80=99m going to double down. I don=E2=80=
=99t want to have a super distributed workforce. I want people to be more i=
n one or two offices, help me take those three countries, four countries to=
 open up big offices into and hire aggressively into and help me run payrol=
l there.=E2=80=9D Or =E2=80=9CLet me try it out with a couple people here a=
nd there and see how it goes=E2=80=9D. So those conversations are happening=
 at the enterprise level, I still think there=E2=80=99s a huge gap in that =
knowledge where most people leaders haven=E2=80=99t fully figured out globa=
l. And even if they have, it=E2=80=99s usually very disconnected with local=
 HR in every country and the global head of HR and has some form of visibil=
ity, but not enough visibility to truly own it.

*Do you have a big sales force or is this mostly a =E2=80=9CThey find you f=
or one specific thing=E2=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s a land-and-expand model?*

*AB:* We have a pretty good go-to-market team to be completely honest. We h=
ave a pretty big sales force, I think about five hundred, six hundred plus =
people. I=E2=80=99ll say, it=E2=80=99s a pretty even split between inbound =
and outbound as well. But yeah, definitely go-to-market has been one of the=
 strengths on that front for sure. The thing is our ACV [annual contract va=
lue] is really high if you think about it.

*Very good. I find your company really fascinating, because number one, it =
slots into a sort of broad-based model of companies that can be built these=
 days, which is you=E2=80=99re like an API for worldwide employment. You pl=
ug in on both sides, so that=E2=80=99s compelling. The second thing though =
is the broad-based question of what=E2=80=99s happening to the white collar=
 workforce broadly and the real benefits that are going to accrue to your c=
lassmate in Croatia and the risks that perhaps will accrue to your classmat=
es in the Valley and there=E2=80=99s lots of interesting angles to think ab=
out in that regard. You actually reached out to me and I was immediately ho=
oked and compelled and I=E2=80=99m glad we could get a chance to talk about=
 it.*

*AB:* Yeah, we=E2=80=99re very excited about what the future holds on that =
front. I think like you said, the world is becoming more borderless, it=E2=
=80=99s a very timely product and I think global hybrid, how you=E2=80=99re=
 going to manage your workforce is in the mind of every CEO and HR leader. =
Like you said, there=E2=80=99s a decent product-founder fit, I like to thin=
k and as we build this out, we=E2=80=99ll have some very interesting insigh=
ts on how the word will kind of shape up and with the new product, with the=
 HR infrastructure coming up, we are actually going to have full visibility=
 on the full workforce of our customers. So, this is going to give us an ev=
en better angle in terms of understanding how they=E2=80=99re thinking abou=
t managing their global workforce. Very excited about this too and thank yo=
u for answering. Very happy to speak with you.

*Absolutely, thanks for coming onto Stratechery. It was great talking.*

*AB:* Thank you so much.

